body.description:
Define the abstract BaseShim class. Every device needs a shim — the translation and management layer between the device's native interface and the rack contract.

Problem: Shims are where lifecycle (start/stop/restart/self_test/rollback) lives. Without an abstract base, each shim diverges and loses the uniform interface guarantee.

Proposed shape:
- agent_datacenter/shim.py:
  from abc import ABC, abstractmethod
  class BaseShim(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def start(self) -> bool: ...  # True = success
    @abstractmethod
    def stop(self) -> bool: ...
    @abstractmethod
    def restart(self) -> bool: ...
    @abstractmethod
    def self_test(self) -> dict: ...  # {passed: bool, details: str}
    @abstractmethod
    def rollback(self) -> None: ...  # called if start() fails
    @property
    @abstractmethod
    def device_id(self) -> str: ...  # unique device identifier

Affected files:
- ~/dev/src/agent_datacenter/agent_datacenter/shim.py

Design rules:
- oop-first: ABC with abstractmethod; device_id as abstract property forces every shim to declare its target
- docs-in-code: module docstring explains shim responsibility (translate native interface, own lifecycle)

Scope boundary:
IN: abstract base shim only
OUT: any concrete shim implementations (those are Postgres/Igor/Claude device tickets)

Test plan:
- Class inheriting BaseShim missing start() raises TypeError on instantiation
- self_test() return type documented as {passed: bool, details: str}
- device_id property is abstract (subclass must declare)
